folder: Minetta Street & Minetta Lane, Manhattan, NY
text:
Minetta Street, south from but not including Minetta Lane, to and including Bleecker Street. Nos. 2-8 Minetta Street, (on the extreme right) are frame houses with brick fronts. In the background is seen the Roman Catholic Church of Our Lady of Pompeii on Bleecker Street, at the S.W. corner of Downing Street.

folder: Minetta Street & Minetta Lane, Manhattan, NY
text:
Minetta Street, north from its bend to Minetta Lane. At the left are two 3-story buildings, No's. 12 and 14 that are to remain and separate two modern 6-story apartment houses. The preparatory stages of that one at the S. W. corner can be barely perceived. This was reported in the N. Y. Times of December 16, 1939. A report dated September 9, 1940 announces the second at
No's 2-10. This will be at the left margin.

The 3-story residence in the background is No. 16 Minetta Lane and adjoins the warehouse at No. 12.

April 13, 1940
P. L. Sperr

folder: Minetta Street & Minetta Lane, Manhattan, NY
text:
Minetta Street (left) at the S.W. corner of Minetta Lane (right) and southward, showing the preparatory stage for a new 6-story apartment house on this site. Thru the clearance appear buildings that are across 6th Avenue. Predominant is the new Roman Catholic Church of Our Lady of Pompeii. This is at the N.W. corner of the Carmine and Bleecker Streets.

Note the bend in Minetta Street and the isolated structures remaining on its west side. These are No's 12 and 14. Another apartment house is to be erected to abut on the far side of same as per the N.Y. Times of September 9, 1940. This site was formerly occupied by several frame buildings with brick fronts. At their rears was an inner court, Minetta Place. On the extension of 6th Avenue this and its rear buildings were exposed to view and subsequently obliterated.

April 13, 1940
Views 1, 2
P.L. Sperr
